Spéculation agricultural
The German bank examines in detail the speculation on the raw
In Christian Teevs
The German bank abandons - her speculation on commodities?
According to information SPIEGEL ONLINE - Josef Ackermann instructed a working group to seek the consequences of speculation for the world's poor.
In January, the leader of the group is then draw the consequences.
Hamburg -
For the citizens of the Federal Republic, the thing is clear: According to a study, 84 percent of Germans find unacceptable that banks are speculating on commodities like corn and wheat.
Two thirds of respondents even require the German bank and other credit institutions discontinuent this avenue of business because it increases the problems of the poorest in the world.
It is the result of a Forsa survey on the order of the consumer group Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid October.
The author Harald Schumann said in this article that speculation on the commodity markets, pushing global prices and that banks share a complicity to global hunger.
The campaign of consumer protection is specifically against the head of Deutsche Bank, Josef Ackermann, - even if large banks such as Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley act the same way.
The speculation on commodities was originally introduced to protect merchants against price fluctuations.
But the majority of experts share between - time that bettors have posted offers and demand - and benefit at the expense of the very poor.
Ackermann was responding to criticism differently US competitors: He promised to investigate the accusations and said, "no matter is worth put at stake the reputation of Deutsche Bank.".
According to information SPIEGEL ONLINE an international working group is currently examining the charges of Foodwatch - Report.
The review should be completed by the end of the year, then the results of the board of Deutsche Bank must be submitted - with recommendation, usual.
In January, the head of the Bank will indicate the consequences.
It could result in a reduction of the commodities market, or even a complete abandonment.
Ackermann built its Image
The head of Foodwatch Thilo Bode has welcomed the news, but at the same time, confirmed its criticism of the financial sector: "The speculation on rising food prices shows a draconian way, how the banks today are harmful to the general interest."
Ackermann is the first banking lobby to be today especially under obligation.
"The Deutsche Bank must remove all investments in its portfolio, for which the money was invested on food speculation," said Bode.
"It matters little, for Mr Ackermann, if it is a question of starving people or if the reputation of the Deutsche Bank is at stake."
The awareness of Ackermann may seem at first sight surprising, but it is clear that the chief executive of the group wants to present a perfect image, a few months before leaving office.
The Deutsche Bank did announce Monday that the president of the Council of Administration will not change what is planned in the Council of Administration.
He could improve his image with an abandonment of agricultural speculation.
And about potential losses, it did little to concern - his successor will be.
A on two would terminate the investments in commodities.
Foodwatch strives to maintain a strong pressure on the Manager.
So far more than 30,000 people have already participated in the campaign organization.
Bode released the survey Tuesday, with which the 7 and 8 November the Forsa Institute has completed questionnaires from 1001 people.
Just 11 percent found it legitimate that Deutsche Bank proposes investments for which bets on the price of food products are made.
Many customers of the bank would also personal consequences if they knew that their bank is involved in such operations: one in two would terminate, following the poll, all the investments for which money is injected in speculation on commodities.
43 percent déconseilleraient of such a bank to their entourage, 49 percent said they think the termination of their account to change to bank. "
21st home in Vienna
The Pavilion who moved
On the Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian flag for global exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 has won awards, has been a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruins.
Now it is again open and takes the place of house of exposure.
If there is enthusiasm for an architecture after - modern war, for his clear forms, its hangars in glass, and her bold and its new building materials that are typical of the belief to technical progress, then the flag of the Austrian architect Karl schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels Expo is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion received once the "Grand Prize of Architecture" for its construction, steel and glass and suspended.
The construction is seen up to our days as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He has made the architects so famous, he has also built the Pavilion for Expo next Austrian.
With his legendary home to four cylinders of BMW and its adjacent construction in the form of bowl in Munich, he finally became famous at international level in 1973.
His draft flag as a temporary construction had been exposed after the exhibition in the Garden Switzerland to the station south of Vienna, has been transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was not physically or technically suitable for a museum - not walls to hang the works of art, not a good environment.
However, it was also long used, "so that contemporary art gets a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building was empty and is increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "House of the 21st century" and will be in future used as museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday night the Belvedere museum opened, which owns the house, the first exhibition - a chance at any point of view.
The new departure was led by Agnes Husslein - Arco, which became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere.
Husslein - Arco, has promoted an art historian to a considerable career in his youth, artistic skater in Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the museum of modern art of Salzburg, it led to the conversion work with politicians and the protection of monuments, it received public funds and private sponsorship and established the operation.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exposed, a cafe and a bookstore there, and an office must be built.
Surveillance strict, small budget
For the implementation Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had transformed and expanded with sensitivity secession of Joseph Olbracht and that he had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the flag was "extremely important" a place where he had seen "virtually every weekend" exhibitions.
He knew the project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness following his trip to Vienna and by his change of use.
At the current changes, there were big problems: the building was "a chasm in energy," said Krischanitz.
The profiles of the facades in glass windows were changed, insulating glass fibre reinforced glass was asked and the roof replaced by a particular safety glass.
The beams thermal bridges have been strengthened or replaced, and coatings filled with asbestos have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a sign of light tamisé between home and road ensures lighting, a bridge leading to the entry - it is almost a new construction, but still the Schwanzer Pavilion.
The exterior doors of origins remained, the house is painted in a shade protection against rust red, brown.
And the cinema is identical to what it once was.
And all under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive were to be found, and that appeal to the Office of the protection of monuments," said Krischanitz and it draws attention to a gross floor in basement.
Despite all the constraints, the problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
That would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels," said Krischanitz recently, a story typical of "Drop - in - the - City.".
Such architecture is "still in the wrong place" and wants to "awaken the good conscience.".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because there is a chance of urban construction: around the Garden Switzerland is precisely the "area of the station" newly planned, with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may happen: the House of the 21st century could benefit from the construction of another Krischanitz places, because the Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin-based temporary art center, and as he said, it is already negotiating with the city to get a site in the vicinity of the Garden Switzerland.
