The mass slaughter staff
The new book by Peter Englund offers depth and generosity. Titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War" (Beauty and the Sorrow: an intimate history of the First World War), it begins with a long list of characters who you greenhouse the heart.
A council to start: déchirez carefully this page and into your marque-page.
You will learn to know these people in detail. In this storybook tale of Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon in these few moments where, as one of its men or women, you will be disturbed and desperate in the fog of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish journalist and historian.
It is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for literature.
He wrote a book out of the ordinary that he described, accurately, as "a book of anti-histoire."
It contains a few names, treaties important or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion on the strategies and equipment.
This is not a book about what happened, he said, "a book describing what it could look like.". It is the "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"The beauty and grief" summarizes the experiences in time of war 20 men and women more or less ordinary, the two sides of the war, young schoolgirls and botanists to escaladeurs, passing by doctors, paramedics and sellers.
Some will become heroes.
Other prisoners of war. Some will lose members, will become mad or lose life.
Their lives are vacillating here as a church candles: while some extinguishing rightwinger, new.
The book by Peter Englund departs from the history books.
It has the idea that the First World War is that by the terrible war trenches on the Western Front.
"The beauty and grief" described deftly other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the eastern front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tse-tse flies boisterous are a problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people as a natural disaster, such a hurricane Katrina which stinks the cordite still hanging.
When cannon shots echoed in the distance, and you're a stay-at-home mom, are you staying or fuyez-vous?
Who will come anyway?
Almost nobody can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts was expanded by assumptions, expectations, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"The beauty and grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny within the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a sailor of the German fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are more preserved through the accumulation of small moments and details.
Most address the deprivation and the ability to get by.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, ersatz everywhere."
"Café, fake imitation of aluminum, rubber, paper, bandages wooden buttons."
He continued on the replacement food in Germany.
He described the "meat made of crushed rice cooked in fat mutton (and over with a false bone of wood); tobacco manufactured with roots dry and the dried skin of potatoes; wooden soles of shoes."
He says that "837 permitted substitute meats are recorded in the production of sausages. It also find 511 cafes."
Some stories deal with honour and courage.
An American acknowledges its own impulse to the savagery and says about the war: "You feel that, after all, is what the men were intended, rather than sit in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and rather than pretending that such a veneer is synonymous with civilization, and that there is no barbaric behind your shirt empesée and cloutée.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes he may die, and that nobody will notice or pay attention.
"When is resigned to sacrifice, we hope to have an audience," he wrote.
It is unfortunately rather comparable to "a man strangled in secret.".
Other comments relate to the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
"The conflict becomes more of a history of economic competition," said Peter Englund, "a war between the factories.".
It captures the arrival of what he called "a new species within the aviary at the beginning of the century: the mass murderer well-balanced and convinced ideologically, clothes well tailored, who executes his butchery while sitting behind a counter."
People act unexpectedly behaviour; there is so much that heroism.
Peter Englund talks about soldiers who tried to catch a vénérienne disease among prostitutes in order to avoid the service at the front.
"It is the most grotesque in the trade of more due to gonorrhea, that the soldiers" buy and cover the genitalia in the hope of finishing in the hospital, "he wrote.
"The more desperate to apply on the eyes, which translates into a blindness to life."
In this translation of Swedish by Peter Graves prose, Peter Englund is flexible but not ostentatious, perfectly suited to its task of humanity.
In dozens of short scenes, it captures how the war has "triggered exclusively uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, a social revolution, an aversion to religion."
People are beginning to ask why their leaders are a war.
The best books on the First World War are often indirect, as "Great War and Modern Memory" (The Great War and Modern Memory) Paul Fussel, or "In the west nothing new," Erich Maria Note, rather than complete.
The book by Peter Englund is an unconventional pantheon.
The end of the book is the most overwhelming that I have read in a non-fictionnelle.
I do not reveal.
