The union of school aid is suing the city for redundancies
The union that represents hundreds of school aid who lost their jobs last month plans to bring a trial in the city for layoffs unnecessary and discriminatory. The impact is disproportionate on schools serving disadvantaged pupils.
The lawsuits are probably the ultimate weapon of the union, the Council of the 37th District, to try to overturn the dismissals.
Six hundred seventy-two school aid, coordinators of parents and other employees, part of the less well paid, City have lost their jobs on October 7. The union leaders have compared these redundancies to a political revenge for not having left the city access to a fund for health care led by groups of workers, and that would have helped close the budget gap last spring.
The municipal authorities have denied the charge.
At a City Council hearing last month, Chancellor Dennis M. Walcott said the layoffs were part of the budget closed in June.
A member of the Council responded, mentioning that layoffs of school aid n "were not specified in the budget.
The officers of the Council of the 37th District said they meet a notice of claim, warning the education department that he would be prosecuted; a press conference will be held Wednesday to officially announce the lawsuits in State Supreme Court in Manhattan.
Dennis M. Walcott and the Department of the education of the city will be the defendant. The complainants will be represented by eight workers made redundant, all black or Latin American origin, as most school aid that have lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, spokesman of the legal department of the city, said that the municipality has not yet been able to see the reasons of the trial and therefore cannot comment on the allegations.
According to a draft of complaints received by the New York Times, the union backing the number of redundancies in schools in the most deprived areas of the city to support his complaint against unfair treatment, saying that the poorest schools would lose the most aid due to underfunding.
While there are no dismissal on Staten Island, and some barely in Upper East Side or TriBeCa, 17 school aid have lost their jobs in the 23rd District of Brownsville, and 46 in the 8th and 9th Districts neighborhoods south of the Bronx.
Noting the loss of five school aid on eight employed at Public School 36 in Harlem, where 68 percent of students live in poverty, the prosecution say "This is not a neighborhood of well-off parents who can get funds to fill the gap."
The budget of the "public school 36 has been reduced by 3.26 percent this year. Funds have also been lost when the city has changed its calculation of the entry of additional funding for each pupil."
The union also says that the directors of schools have been misled by some terms in a memo authorizing the dismissal of coordinators of parents.
The memo employed the term "overshooting" to describe the action, even if "excess" described more generally the action of moving a teacher of a school to a group of available workers whose salaries are paid by the central office.
According to the project of complaints, "66 parent coordinators were laid off," and "not only for cause."
Mission completed: Congress to find agreement on the issue of Libya
It would appear that Republicans and Democrats have reached an agreement on Capitol Hill on the issue of the uprising in Libya.
It took an uprising succeeded, the capture and death of longtime dictator Muammar Gaddafi as well as U.S. involvement.
The Senate Foreign Relations Committee will take a decision next Tuesday, supported by President John Kerry (Democrat - Massachusetts), with Sens. John McCain (Republican - Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Independent, Connecticut), clapping the Libyan people for their revolt and American troops for their "courage".
"This resolution is to honour the courage of the Libyans when they begin to rebuild their country," Kerry said.
"This is a bipartisan support to their democratic aspirations."
The language may be harmless but the debate on Libya has never been easy so far.
This summer, lawmakers of both parties came into conflict, as well as with the White House, on the wording of several resolutions to approve or not the U.S. military role in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain have presented a resolution to authorize the limited use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The bill was defeated by a wide bipartisan margin and has never been the subject of a vote in the Senate.
But the same day of the failure of the bill, the House of Deputies also rejected a measure to reduce the funding of U.S. operations in Libya.
The U.S. mission is therefore remained under a form of purgatory legislature - the Congress sufficiently upset to criticise the management of the mission by Obama, but not enough for him out of the sails.
The indecisiveness of Congress has been overtaken by events.
Tripoli fell under the insurgents in August and Gaddafi was killed last October 20.
The NATO mission officially ended on 31 October.
The Senate can now act.
The resolution of the Committee on Foreign Relations "congratulate the Libyan people for his extraordinary courage and determination for freedom" and "congratulate the men and women of the U.S. armed forces and their coalition partners engaged in military operations to protect the Libyan people, for their courage and great professionalism."
The resolution also says "the national interest of the United States to reach a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya."
The EU 's new measure all the support of the Senate Foreign Affairs Committee or divisera-t-elle lawmakers like last June?
Sen. and Chairman of the Board Richard D. Lugar (Independent) objected to the latest version.
His spokesman said last Monday that Richard D. Lugar had not yet read the latest version of new project.
In the Capitol, the House must vote this week an amendment to the Constitution to achieve a balanced budget, a legislative priority for nearly all congressional Republicans and some Democrats.
The measure, supported by the Republican Bob Goodlatte (Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment on the budget, or any other issue, to get a floor vote in the House or the Senate.
Other lawmakers have so far failed to approve their amendments, but it is not without trying.
The amendment is part of the 68 Goodlatte constitutional amendments have been introduced in Congress on a broad range of topics.
Some are recurrent - the same bill proposed in both the House and the Senate - and others are slight variations of a precedent.
There are at least 15 versions in the House only the amendment for a balanced budget, and another handful who "would control federal spending.".
Some of these bills are identical, but give their support - including the new Republicans who want to gild their CV - the chance to boast of being "author" of such a measure.
The law on the control of the budget (Budget Control Act) approved last August asked the vote of the House and Senate on the amendment to a balanced budget.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment.
Beyond the budget, several members want to limit the number of warrants during which members of Congress can serve, while Jose E. Serrano (Democrat - New York) wants to lift the limit of two terms for presidents.
Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Democrat - Illinois) has proposed a multitude of amendments guaranteeing the right to a quality education and health care, among other topics.
An amendment prohibiting marriage between individuals of the same sex is proposed, like the amendment prohibiting the desecration of the flag.
Some lawmakers also want to allow the cancellation of federal laws if two-thirds of the states are opposed.
So eager were the members to offer amendments, they are not as fast as in the past.
In the 111th Congress, lawmakers have proposed 77 amendments, and introduced 66 at the 110th.
The pace slows in the early 1990s, when the members were generally more than 150 amendments every two years, according to figures provided by the Senate library.
But these amendments were not much more successful than they have today.
The last amendment to have been added - the 27th - was ratified in 1992 but proposed to Congress in 1789.
