The absolutely contradictory impressions illustrate the difficult relations that have installed between the military and an American public passionate but often distant.
There are lavished praise the troops for their sacrifices.
But they have a certain price, say some military.
The public is increasingly as if he was sorry for the men and women in uniform.
"We are not at all," said Brig. Gen. Sean B. MacFarland, who led the troops in Iraq and will leave soon for Afghanistan.
"But it seems that the only way to support us to lock ourselves in the role of spirits unlucky."
It is a very sensitive subject for the military leaders, who do not want to seem not grateful or disagree with the public they serve.
They also realize that the anger of revenantes troops of the Vietnam War was much worse.
Thus, most conversations on the mercy in confidence among the veterans.
After the return of his two sons of combat with the Marines, retired Colonel Mark Cancian warned that the public would consider their service from two perspectives.
Some people would watch with respect because they were facing insurgents and have traveled to distant lands.
Others will ask if "a veteran angry and violent hiding under the surface," said Cancian, who fought in Iraq and returned to work for the Government to Washington.
When he was looking for a job, he said, he felt that a few people who were the subtle way talks asked if he would be able to cope under the stress of a demanding job in Washington immediately after his return.
"When you raise the subject of the service, you are facing negative impressions," said Colonel Cancian when he speaks to his son.
The military difficulties arise, in part, from the American indifference to the wars.
The victories are rarely congratulated by a country as unfamiliar with the military and which sees little direct benefits of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
"As a nation, we value more heroism in the same way as the Second World War," said retired Lieutenant General David Barno, who led the troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, the congratulations of politicians and the people focus largely on the depth of the suffering of the military.
The troops are recognized for the number of periods of services endured, the number of friends lost or the extent of the injuries.
The army face growing pressure to crack down on rapists
This week, a hearing will decide whether capital 28 men and women will go on trial against the army for alleged inaction on rape.
The case, hundreds of plaintiffs prepare the next.
Private First Class Elizabeth Lyman was aged 25 years and 11 weeks pregnant the night she says she was raped by a soldier.
It was in October 2008. She was returning to his barracks in Miramar Air Station, north of San Diego, after having dinner with a friend, when she met a colleague carrying a six-pack of beer.
He asked if he could join in his bedroom for a drink.
"C" was a wake-up call, "said Elizabeth Lyman.
But the Texane has set aside his concern.
I thought: no, it has 19 years.
"It is the Texas," she said.
"I will have to follow my intuition."
A few minutes after entering the bedroom Elizabeth Lyman, the man was grabbed from behind, thrown by land and raped, claims.
This week, on 18 November, Elizabeth Lyman and 27 other soldiers, some still in service and not others, will wait with anxiety the court decision during a historic trial which will take place in Arlington, Virginia, and who will decide whether a trial against the former defence secretary Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, will take place.
They are accused of not having stopped the widespread rape within the military, thus going against the constitutional rights of soldiers.
Ranked in February by Susan Burke, a lawyer in Washington, the trial involved the departure 17 plaintiffs. That number rose to 28 months - 25 women and 3 men, all claiming to have been raped or sexually abused by fellow soldiers. They also claim that the army has not investigated, prosecuted or provided adequate justice after the alleged attacks.
Susan Burke says in galonnées military, because the problem starts by them.
"The army is a vertical structure," she said.
"Who are the individuals in a position to" eradicate the culture of retaliation? The leaders. "
The lawyer also said that since February, she was contacted by almost 400 other survivors, most of which could be part of future lawsuits.
His strategy: instead bring all the plaintiffs in this case - putting all its eggs in one basket - it will start several trial, if necessary, to maintain the pressure.
The defence team, for the Defense Department, led by the US attorney Neil MacBride, filed a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents, obtained by Newsweek, detail the strategy of defence, and essentially the fact that the military cannot be pursued by soldiers in service or not for injuries caused in the armed forces.
According to a 1950 decision of the Supreme Court, called the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries suffered by staff in active service.
"The alleged evil is inherent to military service of the complainants" indicate the documents.
The Defense Department declined to comment.
Things have changed since the 1950s.
While women have still not, officially, the right to go into combat, this distinction is listed on paper: the front lines of the recent wars are only rarely.
In Iraq as in Afghanistan, teams of soldiers women play an increasingly important role, particularly in contact with the local women.
Result: on these two wars, 150 women soldiers lost their lives - two-thirds in combat situations.
It is time for the army to modernise says Susan Burke.
It is not only to fight: three other trials are underway in more of its own.
At the Yale law school, the center of legal services for veterans is preparing a case against the four main military academies for allegedly encouraging an atmosphere misogynistic.
On the other hand, the nonprofit foundation Vietnam Veterans of America is preparing a lawsuit against the army, focusing on the diagnosis of "personality disorders" awarded to victims of rape to give them leave - a relatively ordinary, according to activists such as Anu Bhagwaru of the Service Women's Action Network (network of military action), a group for human rights.
His group has filed a lawsuit in December at the Veterans Administration, accusing them of discriminatory practices in the handling of applications for benefits for people who have been victims of sexual assault in the service.
Nine bills independent of each other have been introduced in Congress by a bipartisan mix of senators and representatives, offering various solutions.
In 2010, 3,158 sexual assaults were recorded after the centre of intervention and prevention of sexual assault (Sexual Assault Prevention and Response Office) of the Department of Defence.
But it is well known that the number of sexual assaults is underestimated. Indeed, after the Pentagon's own estimate, this figure represents about 13.5 percent of the 19,000 incidents this year.
The report appeared in March is also studying the percentage of lawsuits: in 2010, 20 percent of cases in the military have been the subject of a trial - half the percentage of the civilian judicial system.
The plaintiffs in the case of Susan Burke describe their aggression as the first of a series of injuries.
In the case of Lyman, it informs the Military Police of rape less than an hour after the facts.
That night, she says, asked to tell 11 times in detail his rape at different police, doctors and commanders.
She suffered a "rape kit" (literally a rape kit), and the blood of her attacker - due to a cut to his arm - was found in his bed.
Six months later, in April 2009, Elizabeth Lyman is sitting before a judge, a trial in which we asked about his sexual relations with her boyfriend earlier the day of the attack.
Six people testified as character witnesses for the perpetrator of the crime, which was eventually acquitted.
"I remember the day when the verdict was delivered," said Elizabeth Lyman.
"I thought I was going to start having contractions. I am crying after the court."
"I have been placed in psychiatric unit, and when I'm out, I remember saying to my commander" This was not his trial but mine. "."
Elizabeth Lyman was forced to see a military psychiatrist, who finished by diagnose a personality disorder, making it unfit for service.
In January 2010, she has been referred under the terms less than honourable, preventing him from receiving any advantage.
