The walls have eyes: researchers studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the extreme right in Europe's Anders Behring Breivik was just a guy doing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who said he was taken to a murderous madness in Norway in July, leaving 77 victims, was facing his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, it was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, to discuss with some of the millions of nationalists who support the far-right groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how?
Easy... Connectez-vous to Facebook.
"We realized that it was not so difficult that it to find them," said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report released recently by the think-tank on digital DEMOS populism in Europe.
Facebook is so full of personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they seek with scientific precision - the way the mercaticiens do for years.
The team of Jamie Bartlett has discovered that half a million members are fans far-right groups in Europe. It has targeted with the ads, but instead to link it to a new group or product announcements, inviting users to respond to an inquiry. The questions related to their education level, their attitudes to the violence and their optimism about their own future.
In coming into contact with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 followers of 14 right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"This is a new way of doing research," said Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those that combine online activism and hors-ligne are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen."
The "study of DEMOS is only an example on how Facebook has become the new essential tool in the hands of scientists.
The groups of reflection, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all the issues that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to the "I love," publications on the walls and updated statutes.
With more than 800 million active users who add content on average three per day, "the supernova data" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research site whose name appears in the title of almost 800 percent over the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people that you could not get in the street.
"Before, when you try to carry out investigations on the people of the British National party, it was very difficult to identify."
"You have to go to the party, but you would never have allowed to enter," said Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could offer a way to identify and deal with the social and health problems.
According to a recent study of D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin - Madison, and colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook their exploits drunk were much more likely to be alcoholics that students discreet about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as advisers, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student whose status would speak too often alcohol.
"You can't deal with a problem if you don't has diagnosed," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the centre for health, behavior and the development of children in the Research Institute for children located in Seattle, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and which are not recognized in another case."
Facebook also constantly access to information of its users.
The team of the site which handles data has studied the statistics on the situation in love and the day of the Saint Valentine, the rate of participation in the 2010 midterm elections and a national happiness index (information only available - champions digital freedom have long argued that the site could make available its trove of data to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site notes, that they like it or not - in exchange for power play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometres, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation which they have not even heard?
While researchers have clearly defined instructions on how to collect the information other than through the Internet, it is anything else online.
"I do not believe that a large number of users have already thought to the fact that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the Laboratory Knowledge of London, according to a 2006 study he conducted in observing the Facebook walls of its students.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study to be completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the truth of a profile or on the wall of a user.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two entirely different things," says Neil Selwyn.
That is why, despite his experience as a researcher, Neil Selwyn think a notebook and a pen remain the best tools we can use.
"Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people," he said.
"The social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and the social, this is not in front of a computer."
