7 lessons of the interview lost Steve Jobs, film this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on 5 October, some have compared to Henry Ford - qualified by the technical genius and inventor of the modern computer.
But what Apple fans can find more telling in an interview of Steve Jobs found recently and which will be released this week in the first part of a film on the main markets, is how the creative spirit had understood the process and work flow products.
It was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified to a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a améliorateur of rolls - a man who believed that many business leaders had a "disease their suggesting that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work between a clever idea of a product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Nerds.". This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sits down for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years ago that Steve Jobs had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he said that the main copies disappeared in transport.
It is only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full video is found in the garage of the director.
This video, slightly rebound, is the basis of the film 68 minutes entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be broadcast to the cinema next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate the detailed interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic to expose philosophies technological and business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs is clearly his thoughts, in order to give a precise answer.
We also find times when the perfectionism of Steve Jobs resurfaced, where it seems eager to hear the issues of Cringely, giving him shots for the elbow to speed up and move to questions or issues of greater importance.
Shot before the era of Pixar, the iPod or iPhone, there is something eerily prescient on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs assesses what he considers good or bad in other companies and its own vision on the future of computing.
It is one thing to read the posthumous assessments of the career of Steve Jobs, but there is something of crude and inspiring on the man we see here, the dreamer anxious on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can be and should be.
He explained then put away.
Here is a summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview:
On the way he has learned to run a business:
"During all these years, I have always asked: 'Why are you doing things?" and the answers are always the same:' Oh, simply because it must do. "
No one knows why, no one is looking at things in a company.
That is what I discovered.
Steve Jobs is giving details on its efforts to simplify the accounting at Apple.
my astonishment about how the costs were registered - often begins with a "standard" valued at cost to nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - he has developed an automated factory that guaranteed the precise calculation of trade costs.
On the opportunity to play a round the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" that he founded with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack the phone networks and free telephone longue-distance.
The device has been the subject of many written beforehand, but the euphoria of Steve Jobs here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He described how he and Wozniak have tested the box using a public phone call and then, in a AT&T network to another while bypassing satellite as possible.
"We enveloppions the ball of different things half a dozen times and you hurliez in the public phone and you arrived a minute later the public phone in hand," says Jobs joked.
"We were young and thanks to the Blue Box, we learned that we ourselves create something capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure in the world."
We do not know much, but we have created a small thing capable of controlling big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I do not believe that Apple would have existed without this one day.
Steve Jobs is telling a wonderful round that he and Wozniak have developed: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue box in the middle of the night in posing for Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the US diplomat, the two accomplices are crazy laugh just before the Pope himself is awake.
On his love with technology (and canvassing of Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12 years, the hunt for spare parts to build a fréquencemètre, the number of Bill Hewlett in the directory and is a blow over.
Shortly after their conversation of 20 minutes, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"This has been a remarkable influence on me. It" was the only company that I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a business and how employees are treated. "
Steve Jobs is subsequently become one of HP employees to visit the research laboratories of the company, located in Palo Alto, where he found the "first desktop computer ever designed."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode ray tube. I fell in love.
The teenager that I "was returned in HP and began to write programs for this machine.
On improvisation of innovation:
In several times in the interview, Steve Jobs speaks to invent new products on a whim.
At the beginning of his career, when he moved to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked to assemble a computer.
Working at only 30 days of credit, he had to address the assembly and the delivery of the aircraft finished.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties to develop a computer mouse:
"I remember big wrangling... I cried over claiming that it would take five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I have had enough, I came out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and who proved incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that have stalled:
Even before it does revive Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated the way many industrial leaders would be wrong and losing control of their market share.
"If you work for IBM or Xerox, you made a better or a better printer, copier and after?"
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more success.
Sales and marketing can change, so [these types of people] that eventually lead businesses and staff specializing in product are put on the "gap of decision-making.
The genius in product that has led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can't imagine design a good product versus a bad product - the manual work required.
That is what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could hold all the computer industry.
It could be 10 times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 1990s...
They snatched defeat to victory.
On innovation as art form:
"A huge part of manual work between a clever idea of an exceptional product... as you develop this idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot on its intricacies.
There are compromises to do... Some things you can't do, the electrons can, glass, robots, factories.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) in assembling to each other.
Finally, the decisions are taken by personal taste. It is trying to give you the best products that men have created, and try to bring these things to the product you create.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have always ashamed to steal good ideas.
That is partly what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who have simply been the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for the computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another area.
