The Asian Development Bank has asked India and China to prepare to help the eurozone out of the sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term decline that would prevent the development of the Asian economy. "
Rajat Nag, director general of the BASD based in Manila, said that the two economic powers to the fastest growth of the world should "do everything in their power" to speed up the recovery of the currency area through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He was advised not to the BRIC (Brazil, Russia, India, China) to look at the difficulties of Europe of a "indifferent eye" and reported that a financial support to Asian leaders and resources of Europe would help to avoid a collapse in the long term the "global economy.
"We are all together in this crisis."
"Therefore anyone can help Europe out of the crisis is useful," he told the Financial Times in an interview during the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia may be protected until" at some point but it is not immune. "
"So if China and India can help, that nothing in it."
In recent months, the euro area has been seriously shaken by a sovereign debt crisis.
Recently, the cost of borrowing Italian is dangerously skyrocketed and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The burgeoning crisis of sovereign debt in Europe has stirred up fear that the global economy is in recession, and prompted the appeal of the main emerging economies to come together to help the euro area to find a solution.
Mr Nag has hypothesised that the IMF would bring Asian aid, but he also said that this bilateral assistance - as buying bonds from the financial bailout fund of the United States, the European Financial Stability Fund - offered greater power of negotiations to Asian partners of Europe.
Anand Sharma, Minister of Trade and Industry, said that "India will do everything it can" to help the euro area as its own economy now suffers from a decline in exports and a drying up of arrivals of foreign capital.
"Nobody wants the euro area remains volatile and turbulent," he said.
"We have monumental challenges and we must maintain a high level of growth."
"This is not a choice, it is imperative, because where trouverions-nous work for the tens of millions of our young men and women?"
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help European rich when they face their own economic challenges.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, said that it would be politically very difficult to accept aid to Europe to 1.2 billion Indians, including at least 800 000 live on $2 a day or less.
"One day, they discover that Greeks retire at 50 years and they go on holiday in the sun and they will struggle to swallow," he reported.
Lee Howell, the president of the World Economic Forum, has also asked why the reserves of India should be used to maintain many Greek officials paid well in poorly managed that generate losses, as in the rail sector.
Mr Nag said that the eurozone crisis could cause "significant impact" across Asia.
The forecast of the BASD of economic growth of 7.5 percent in Asia in 2011 / 2012 now face "the risk of loss" because of the threat.
He pointed out that emerging markets vulnerable needed to develop "backup plans" to protect an economic downturn and significant leaks of capital.
Sévères warnings from the Pentagon on the potential cuts to the defence
The Secretary of Defense Leon Panetta, has upped the pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that the imminent automatic budget cuts would undermine national security. It sparked a chain reaction of financial corridors of the Pentagon to the battlefields of Afghanistan, from gatherings of civilians.
The Pentagon already digesting some 450 billion of cuts for the next decade, but now fears that an additional amount of $600 or more cuts be imminent if Congress fails to agree on spending.
"The impacts of these cuts would be devastating for the department," Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to reach a budget deal resulting in what we call sequestration would, 23% reductions and the freeze of many new projects.
"A reduction as important, applied indiscriminately and make the most of our vessels and construction projects unfeasible - you can't buy three quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously harm the other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to senators.
"We would also be forced to separate us from a number of our civilian staff and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we should almost certainly send civilians on leave without pay in order to achieve the objective."
"These changes undermine the faith of those who support our military and our preparation would seriously."
The cuts would affect possibly combat troops, continues Panetta.
"Although the funding in time of war accounts contingency operations abroad is not directly affected by the kidnapping, the war effort would be negatively affected by the severe disruption in the budgets of basis," said Panetta.
"The Contracting staff would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and supervision of contract who support the war.".
"The staff manager salaries would be reduced, leading to delays of payment to the suppliers of war, and the legal and political support would be disrupted.".
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of the automatic cuts on the Ministry of Defence.
"The consequence of a kidnapping on the Defense Department would trigger a rapid decline of the United States as undisputed world leader of military power.".
"We are vehemently opposed to this drastic action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday after - noon at the publication of the letter to Panetta.
"This is not a result with which we can live, and this is certainly not the one that we should impose.".
"The kidnapping is a threat to national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen."
What the letter to Panetta and recent warnings of senators will increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon cuts, remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken about possible cuts, even if it is reached itself at the top Pentagon post with years of expertise in the budget to Congress and the White House and knowing he was facing difficult choices.
At a news conference last week, Defense Secretary painted a bleak picture of what could happen - one with a shell but no core.
"This is a ship without sailors.".
"It is a brigade without bullets."
"This is a fighter plane, without enough trained pilots.".
"This is a paper tiger, an army barracks, buildings and bombs which did not have enough trained soldiers able to accomplish the mission," Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a force depressed, ill-prepared and unable to confront potential adversaries.".
"De facto, it invites aggression."
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta outlined specifically how further cuts could "generate significant operational risks: response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits to our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and risk assumed unacceptable in combat operations future.".
And Panetta said that some of the major defence projects could the axe, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
This list included the F35 Joint Strike Fighter, a new bomber expected, the marine - new generation missile, the new combat ship coastline and the new vehicle, which would replace the Humvee army and navy.
Putting an end to the development and testing of the F35 could generate 80 billion in savings over 10 years, but his supporters say it is an essential step of improvement and response to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines suggests how the deception and lies are ubiquitous in everyday life.
The Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
The directors of Penn State have been accused of perjury for allegedly covered up reports that a football coach to retire has sexually abused boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy has been taken by an open microphone saying to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie destroyed careers and convulsé countries.
The member of Congress from New York and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, went for a fool by issuing denials quickly contradicted by evidence.
The former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violations of campaign financing related to coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, no one who has lived the history will never forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked by lying in his second term on his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating to the school and university are legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave students test answers to do on their assessments of performance.
The mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How deception meet - we?
On any given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of those - these are lies.
Another study showed that foreigners to lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
To detect or identify lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game similar to, say, charades, where the aim is to said: "I have had," the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities have conducted a thorough search of such projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths on lies were démystifiés.
The liars look at you in the eye.
They bégayent, blush or are not always.
Do not conclude that the liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, the facial micro-expressions, the training of the question and the response time.
I spent several years to review scientific results in the vast body of knowledge and always emerge on the deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern competence that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, the interviews, the negotiation or management.
The good liars are adept at reading others, putting them at ease in managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that the extravertis lie more than the introvert, the men say more focused on them "lies" while women say more lies "focused on the other" - usually to protect the feelings of someone - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an infidel, others will feel less guilty of you lie.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, look at the normal behaviour of your subject.
That is what we call "establish benchmarks.".
This helps to provide a benchmark to measure future changes.
Look at the posture of your subject, laughter, the voice quality.
You have to know if someone is moving normally his feet continuously in order not to make accusations unfair when you see stir the feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then looking for clues of deceptive behaviour verbal and non-verbal.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
The misleading people can stop the upper body when they try to remember their history, they can point their feet toward the door, looking towards an exit, change of posture significantly or present a post-interview "relief" - a sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult issues are.
The interrogators often falsely indicate that the maintenance is completed just to seek to trigger the reaction post-interview.
Therefore, made the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson has slid using the past while claiming that his wife murdered was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
The individuals misleading language can also use a beat: "I have not had sexual relations with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat entirely a difficult issue.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "language of wood" during his response to a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember assets... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize the deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid the victimization by scammers in their professional and personal life.
