A few days after the Obama administration has threatened to delay the approval of a pipeline project between Canada and the Gulf of Mexico - prompting the ire of unions while appeasing environmentalists - the company seeking to build the pipeline said it is ready to redirect the project to the back on track.
TransCanada said Monday that it will move the proposed pipeline outside the area ecologically sensitive dunes of Nebraska, and is confident that the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a news conference at the Capitol Nebraska.
The official of TransCanada, Alex Pourbax, says that the company remains confident that it will eventually get the approval of a pipeline, but with a different route.
This follows the announcement by the State Department last week that it would delay its decision granting a federal permit for the project until it receives further studies of potential routes to avoid areas of the dunes of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, vast underground water sources.
"This is a real way forward," said Lee Terry, a Nebraska Republican Fox News.
The new environmental review commissioned by the State Department probably would have delayed any decision until 2013, after the elections next year, although officials deny the involvement of the policy in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the decision of the Department of State, and he expressed his support.
The 2,735 km pipeline would stretch from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
He carry 700,000 barrels per day since the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do this, it would have to cross six states.
He is hated by environmentalists, but loved by labor groups, which have relied on the estimated 20,000 jobs related to the pipeline.
But the Nebraska lawmakers opposed to this plan are pushing a law to force the remoteness of the area of Sand Hills and the Ogallala aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
The environmental impact study in the State Department found that the project would have only limited negative environmental impacts, but the energy industry said that the inspector general of the Department has ordered a separate investigation of the review process focused on two issues.
One is that a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was a campaign adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, would represent a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a company that was hired to conduct the initial study was an inappropriate choice by its relationship with TransCanada.
