The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The designated prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of economic disaster
The designated prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has jeopardized all we approach the euro area.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that it can form the Government.
It is expected that it presents a cabinet in his majorities by technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume his post.
Monti said he would present the president the outcome of his conversations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner reporters.
Monti has not said explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The framework is now well mapped out," he added.
Monti has completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a time more reduced that normally, while Italy fight a political and financial crisis that pushed the cost of its debt to levels impossible to support.
The new administration headed by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to recover confidence in Italy who had been affected.
In adding pressure on Monti to dispatch, the instability of markets to put the performance of 10-year BTP Italian bonds by - above the 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employers' federation Confindustria, told the media after his meeting with Monti: "We said that we would support the government.".
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy kind of this emergency situation.
The possibilities of success of Monti were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which the crisis has forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result," said Angelino Alfano, party secretary of centre - right.
The support of PDL party, the largest Italian, is significant because until now many of its members were opposed to the Government of majority technocrat that Monti form.
Parliamentary Support
The new government of Monti must have a strong parliamentary support to implement what probably will be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could cause a new and devastating attack of financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks is added to the pressure by observing that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti on Monday began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and organisations juveniles and women.
He will end his tour of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed by Napolitano, who has empowered a rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt are now back to critical levels between the uncertainty on the success of the new prime minister.
Rescuing Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, it would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should persist up to future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions on the fact that politicians will only time to implement the reforms before the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it must be formed only by specialists, an index of their objections to a process required by the financial pressure.
political sources have reported that the mutual suspicion and disagreements between the parties complicate the trial to include political figures.
