Mujica trip to Mexico to consolidate political ties
An official procession, with the Uruguayan President Jose Mujica, and formed of various ministers and bosses, will on Tuesday on a visit to Mexico to expand trade between the two nations and address the political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the high point of a long agenda of meetings with the political authorities, trade and a meeting with the Uruguayan community residents in Mexico, according to the agenda released by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara, will be "conducive to the exchange of information in the political affairs between the two nations," according to information released by the Presidency of the country south - on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking to convince Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France, which took place when the French representative, Nicolas Sarkozy, has included the US south - countries on the list of tax havens, in the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy has threatened to exclude from the international community countries that continue to be tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultations its ambassador to this European country.
Mexico chairs since November the G20, a group of developed and emerging nations highest in the world, and has in effect with the US south - since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The government has tried in recent years to send the tax exchange agreements to get out of the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), integrated by countries that do not implémentent all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
On the trade front, Mexico and Uruguay have been in force since 2004 a Treaty of Free Trade (TLC), which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
