Japan is returning after the earthquake
The GDP rise a 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and puts an end to the downward spiral of the beginning of March
Since March the Japanese economy was severely crippled, even after the devastating earthquake that became nuclear crisis, the worst disaster of the Japanese country since World War II.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo have calculated the material losses to 300,000 million dollars, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to be mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, data of gross domestic product between July and September served to definitively turn the page: GDP has raised a 1.5% from the prior quarter and a 6 percent annualized rate.
Anyone registered the second quarter - for the Japanese fiscal year begins in March 2012 - requires, in addition, the highest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is due, in part, by the recovery of the acquisition of equipment to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, the companies have increased their investments by 1.1 percent, compared to the decline of 0.9 percent of capital spending observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of increases not - interrupted.
However, the true stimulate the Japanese economy is based exclusively on the Keynesian stimulus to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the shortcomings to grow zero.
Japan has awakened thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of GDP.
This variable has raised a 1%, driven by the increase in spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The yen's stigma
Tokyo is handed over to the internal market when the yen the Japanese currency - - has become a "safe-haven" elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the eurozone and the United States forecasts, a privilege that weighs as a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divides, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of large technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, have been responsible for their weak results between July and September the assessment of the yen.
While the markets continue their seats in the peripheral countries of the EU, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda does not drop the guard.
"We must follow the risks persist, as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," reported yesterday the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said that the majority of Member countries have presented in September clearer signals of economic slowdown.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points of the global economy has highlighted that the major powers are curtailed.
Because it fell four decimal points up to 100,4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even by - below the average, which is in the 100 level, dropping eight decimal points up to 99,13 points.
