First in a goal of budgetary savings: the government plans to impose the employees of the private waiting a fourth day before taking charge of a work stoppage.
In clear, specific business agreement, a worker who falls ill would lose four days wages, so at least 15 percent of his monthly income.
A measure that threatens to spark anger, but which would yield EUR 280 million, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, more symbolic: the civil servants waiting a day not compensated in the event of work stoppage (they so far have not waiting period against three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority also stimulus the issue of fraud, targeting this time abuses linked to the work stoppages.
"The checks will be much more important and, in addition, if you are caught, you rembourserez," said Xavier Bertrand on Sunday, November 13.
As for other cases, the announcement effect seem somewhat disproportionate with the reality of fraud to the work stoppages.
This is the subject since 2002 of constant monitoring and offensives policies, which have often borne fruit.
The French not sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
Attardons we first on the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than 237 million euros per diem allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute of research and documentation in health economics, daily allowances in 2008 accounted for 5 percent of health spending, with 11.3 billion euros.
Of this, $46% were the maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% were the judgments disease, or 6.2 billion euros.
And therefore 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French on average 14.5 days of work stoppage, against 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by Alma Consulting Group.
An average to hide some differences: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management site Monster.com, showed that 75% of 40 000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any day off sick.
Another study, this time of the Sickness, states that in 2010, 37% of the judgments were less than 8 days, 22% 8 to 14 days, 15% 15 days a month, 15% of one to three months and 11 percent in the - beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, the French are not more likely that the stoppages.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two researchers of the CNRS showed that between 1994 and 2001, the rate of overall absence (for health reasons or not) perched in France, between 10% and 11%, against 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15 percent in the United Kingdom - or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands -.
The fraud rulings disease is very little work in the black.
As to the fraud, it reached a low scale.
The strengthening of the legislation since 2002 that the systematic checks are on the judgments of more than 45 days.
In 2008, about 1.5 million tests, the CNAM found that 13% of 285 000 made for short-term rulings were "unjustified or too long," 37 050 case.
In the case of judgments of more than 45 days, routinely checked, there were 11% of cases "inappropriate or unwarranted" on 1.2 million, or 132 000.
In total, 169 000 cases "unjustified," on several million employees who had a disease.
A figure which represents little face, for example, of the black economy.
According to the UMP lawmaker Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would be 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, or more than the total cost of the daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud.
