It must legalise euthanasia and assisted suicide, said a committee of experts
The Canadians live in denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, institutions of health care, and doctors are working together to ensure better palliative care, and that - beyond the cases of cancer.
The Canadian company lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk with their doctor the conditions in which they want to die and take provisions to this effect.
It is one of the conclusions of a report by the Royal Society of Canada, which included six experts in various fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The committee recommends that the government to amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when this choice, with a patient deemed competent to take such a decision.
From the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which has compared the quality of death in 40 countries in the world.
If Canada is ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to broach the subject of death.".
Médicalisation or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts are mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the wish that have most Canadians to die at home, $68.6 percent of them eventually dying in the hospital.
Overall, the country is in Quebec that this rate is the highest, with 86% of deaths at the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all the countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalised, there was no evidence that decriminalization of abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on competent persons not willing or not.
On the contrary, said yesterday in a teleconference Jocelyn Downie, author of the report, there would be many more cases go precisely where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalised.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.".
"The assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," said Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians support euthanasia
Remember that 85 percent of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of life to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010.
And 66 percent believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of elderly or disabled has less value.
As for the people who practiced assisted suicide, 41% of respondents felt that they should not be prosecuted.
In terms of retention or termination of care with a patient, the situation is less clear, say the authors of the report.
So, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it is in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a refusal legally valid is not criminal.
The Committee of Experts also urge that health professionals are trained to the duty to respect a refusal by the end of life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, institutions of health care, and doctors are working together to ensure better palliative care, and that - beyond the cases of cancer.
Finally, in the field of palliative sedation or terminal illness, already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee asks that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce the physical pain, such as euthanasia, and it is subject to the same procedures.
Reserves of other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the report of experts of the Royal Society of Canada.
Mr. Pierre Fields, a specialist in health law, called "extreme" the position of experts signatories of the report, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia for the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of life and have more than 18 years could ask what help to suicide," said Mr. Fields, who had consulted yesterday a summary of the report.
Mr. Fields also stresses that the authors of the report seem to put the autonomy of the individual - above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
"in society, he says, there are beacons and constraints.".
The health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the conclusions of the report, she called it "manifesto pro-euthanasia.".
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, in particular the data in the report about the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide were legalised, either in the Netherlands, and Oregon.
