King Abdullah II of Jordan yesterday was the first Arab leader to call President Bashar al-Assad to leave power "in Syria, where 40 civilians and members of the forces of the regime have been killed.
"If Bashar had to heart the interest of his country, he should resign, but it should also create conditions for a new phase of Syrian politics," said King of Jordan's neighbour, Syria, in an interview with the BBC.
For its part, the Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoglu said Turkish mediation efforts undertaken since the beginning of the year with the Syrian regime have failed.
"Those who are not in peace in the Middle East - with their people and cannot meet will leave," he said, referring to Syria, neighbouring country which Turkey adopted an increasingly tough line.
The United States are on their side welcomed a "strengthening of consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime", after the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union.
"The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League, countries like Turkey adopt an increasingly hard" against the repression in Syria, said Mark Toner, a door - floor of the State Department.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the forces of the regime have been killed in the Deraa region in southern Syria, said the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
Two other civilians were killed "in crossfire and shelling with heavy machine guns to Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to the NGO.
At a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Muallem said that the country is "heading towards the end of the crisis.".
It has also reacted strongly to the Arab League decision to suspend Damascus of its work, which is "a dangerous step.".
"Syria does not shrink," he said, adding that "the ourdis plots against Syria will fail.".
After his decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is now studying a "mechanism of protection of civilians" and wants to send 500 members of Arab organizations of human rights, media and military observers in the country.
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe is also said to support the dispatch of UN observers to help protect civilians of the repression of the regime which he said is the "paranoia.".
A new extraordinary meeting of the League is scheduled for tomorrow in Rabat on the implementation of the plan to exit the crisis decided on 2 November and including the withdrawal of forces from cities in the dispute and the release of demonstrators arrested.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, said yesterday "incorrect" the decision of the Arab League, while China urged Syria to implement the plan to exit the crisis, while guarding support possible sanctions against Damascus.
Italy
Monti request time to markets and sacrifices Italians
The future head of the Italian government, Mario Monti, has called for a bit of time to markets to form his team and implement a program, which will include "sacrifices" to recover the lost credibility in the final months of the Berlusconi government.
The former European Commissioner was in discussion with the political parties yesterday before now meet the unions and employers.
It should put in place a relatively small cabinet of technocrats outside Parliament.
"Monti spoke of an important programme with a lot of sacrifices," said Francesco Mr Nucara, MP for one of the many small groups involved in the talks, after he met the President of the Council.
The president of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, said expect Mario Monti requests by a vote of confidence in Parliament to ensure that the new government has enough support.
The consultations will end by the presentation by Mr Monti of a restricted list, probably a dozen ministers, the head of state, Giorgio Napolitano.
Mr Monti said the nervousness of the bond and stock markets yesterday, asking them time.
In "democracy, there are deadlines" to prepare a government and its programme, he said, saying he was "certain that the markets will be patient and understand.".
His appointment by the president had initially been welcomed by the markets, but the concern has regained the upper hand especially after an unexpected fall in industrial production in the eurozone in September.
The first minister designate should be a team consisting mainly of technocrats, although he stressed that he would like to include "political.".
The new government must last until 2013, the date of the next elections, he said.
According to the president of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, the new government will get the confidence of Parliament by Friday.
Mr Monti is committed, once entered office, to work in the emergency and in order that Italy will "protagonist" in Europe.
A door - floor of the European Commissioner Olli Rehn said that "even with a new government, our diagnosis on the Italian economy does not change.".
The EU, convinced that Rome will not reach its goal of a balanced budget in 2013 despite austerity plans adopted in recent months, has asked for new austerity measures.
The "boss of bosses" Emma Marcegaglia, who will on Tuesday, insisted on the need to revive the economy, "because a country that has not of growth may not meet the parameters of deficit.".
Mr Monti, renowned for his competence and independence as European Commissioner (1994 – 2004), represents a "change of time" to Italy after 17 years of "berlusconisme", the "professor" symbolizing the "serious challenge" and "another Italy," according to the editorialists.
The great unknown will be the longevity of his team.
The President Napolitano would avoid early elections because Italy must place by April 2012 to 200 billion euros of government bonds.
A Russian scientist helped Iran's nuclear program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, helped Iran develop a detonator used with a nuclear weapon, said Monday the American NGO specialising in the nuclear risk.
The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) is based on the recent report of the International Agency for Atomic Safety and other documents from the UN agency to identify.
The IAEA said last week its "serious concerns" about a "possible military dimensions" of Iran's nuclear program.
According to ISIS dipping widely in documents of the IAEA, Danilenko, born in 1934, worked for three decades from the 1960s in a Soviet military nuclear center at Chelyabinsk, and would have been involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by the explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, he would have left the center to establish a company producing "nano-diamants" in Kiev.
The economic problems of its society have led to contact the embassy of Iran in Ukraine in 1995.
He then allegedly cooperated in the Iranian program from 1996 to 2002, before his return to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA is "strong indications that the development by Iran of a nuclear detonation system" has been helped by the work of a foreign expert, which not only knew this technique, but, as a Member State has informed the Agency, has worked for most of his career on this technology within the military nuclear programme of his country of origin. ".
The anti-Muslim crimes and offences rose 50%
The crimes and offences against Muslims have risen nearly 50 percent from 2009 to 2010, while at the same time, the other racial and religious violence have fallen slightly or little progress, according to FBI statistics made public Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violence perpetrated against Muslims is past 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, or 49 percent increase, against a rise of 13 percent of the violence against Catholics, a decrease of 4% of offences against Jews and an increase of 14 percent of crimes and offences anti-religious.
The total number of "hate crimes" rose marginally to 6 628 cases, including 47.3 percent motivated by differences of race and 20% by differences of religion, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offences rise again," said the human rights organisation Human rights First, "the increase in antimusulmanes violence is particularly significant," the organization said in a statement.
"Human Rights First has long said that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, must be regarded as a serious violation of human rights," said one of the leaders of the organization, Paul Legendre.
"The US government can and must do more to tackle these abuses," he said, adding that this could happen by improving police reports on "hate crimes".
The "hate crime" in the US federal law is a legacy of the time of the fight for civil rights.
This legislation was adopted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence linked to race, color, religion, origin and now sex.
Twitter changes its platform and is more similar to Facebook
The micro-blogging site Twitter introduced Monday changes in the presentation of his platform, to allow its users to observe the activity of those they follow, which is like a little more than Facebook.
A new tab "activity" and another "name" to follow more legibly online, the activity of other "Twittos," which follows the messages ("tweets") and those who follow you.
This allows whether they follow messages, if they subscribe to new accounts, if they have messages favorites, etc.
This new formula Twitter has been tested on a small percentage of users in August "to be broadcast to the whole network Monday, told AFP the door - floor of Twitter, Carolyn Penner.
Twitter, which was known for its functioning little instinctive, with terms somewhat esoteric (RT to pass a message to someone else, # followfriday to recommend to follow another user) doing the happiness insiders, opens to a wider audience with a handling more comparable to that of the public networks Facebook and Google +.
On the network, users debated with "tweets" decided on the interest of this innovation.
"It is unnecessary, invasive, and it looks like too to Facebook," wrote @ jemb123.
"The functionality Activity will help me to better follow some elements of my Twitter stream," wrote @ dannykronstrom.
Austria
recording of a "golden rule" in the constitution
The coalition government of Social Democrat - Christian Democrat in power in Austria decided Tuesday to put in the constitution a "golden rule" budget in order to reduce public deficits and avoid a possible downgrading by rating agencies Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It is the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann, who was even announced this decision after a council of ministers, while Austrian public debt is 74.6 percent, well above the - the criterion of 60% maximum set by the Maastricht Treaty, but significantly - below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If the solvency of Austria was downgraded one notch, from AAA to AA +, we should pay three billion euros of interests in more each year," said Minister - Christian Democrat Vice-Chancellor and Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is following a request from the summit in Brussels of eurozone members of 26 October: the heads of state and government had called for the registration by the end of 2012 the reduction of public deficits and a return to balanced public accounts in the constitution or a law of equal value.
The device adopted by the Austrian government nears the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a rule. "."
By 2017, the structural deficit should decrease each year of 0.75 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) and, starting in 2017, the structural deficit of the federal state will not exceed each year 0.35% of GDP, while the regional states and municipalities will present balanced budgets.
The aim is to 2020 / 21 public debt below the 60 percent criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
Yen strong
Noda threat of a new intervention on the foreign exchange market
The Japanese prime minister, Yoshihiko Noda, warned Tuesday that the Japanese authorities would intervene again on the foreign exchange market if the yen should continue to mount.
"We will intervene as we did the last time we see excessive volatility" in yen exchange rate, said Mr Noda in the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen was not far from the historical levels that prompted the Japanese authorities to intervene on 31 October.
This day, Tokyo has sold heavily yen against the dollar to lower the value of the Japanese currency which had set a new record of force since 1945 against the greenback.
But the yen is regularly picked up since, boosted by purchases of investors who see it as a "safe haven" in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar rose Tuesday under the 77 yen and the euro fell below the symbolic 105 yen, close to the levels that sparked the last speech.
Before the financial crisis of 2008 - 2009, the dollar was trading at around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
This surge of the Japanese currency hurt exports of the archipelago because it said the cost of products Made in Japan and reduced the value of income from abroad by Japanese firms, when they convert them into national currency.
"Japan fight to rebuild" since the earthquake and tsunami of March 11, which devastated the area of the northern Tohoku - is), Mr Noda said that fears that the rising yen kills in the bud the fragile recovery.
The third global economic power has reconnected with growth in the third quarter - 1.5 percent from the previous quarter - for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound of exports and household consumption June by the disaster.
But the Prime Minister said that the high yen did not reflect "the economic fundamentals of Japan.".
Finance Minister Jun Azumi, called the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened Tuesday a two-day meeting of its monetary policy council, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
But the deputy governor of the institution, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BOJ had already taken "appropriate measures", suggesting that no additional monetary easing was expected Wednesday.
At its last meeting in late October, the rose 5,000 billion yen (47 billion euros) its purchases of Treasuries, to 55,000 billion yen (519 billion euros) the ceiling amounts it devotes to financial securities purchases to flood the market liquidity.
