Energy policy:
the facts should prevail on the dogmas
If it is a subject that we cannot treat from short-term considerations or under the "emotion, it is the energy policy.
The availability and cost of the electricity directly affect purchasing power and on the competitiveness of businesses.
It is healthy that an election date is the opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place that is nuclear.
The debate will only be successful if he explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet ", the" demographic changes will lead to a doubling of demand for electricity by 2050, at least to deprive a huge part of the global population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will have to overcome the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce the electricity, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a subject disappeared from the debate.
The Fukushima accident does none of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in his decision to give up nuclear weapons.
This is the case of Belgium, who submitted his to the need to find a replacement source can replace, or Switzerland, which is just not build the latest generation plants.
Conversely, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, for example, continue their projects with determination.
The United States have decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their park in the construction of a plant suspended after the accident at Three Mile Island.
If the German model, focused on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality frustrates the speech.
The choice of Berlin will be translated by the rise in the price of electricity the energy dependence, a worsened by the increasing reliance on imported gas, especially Russia, a jump of CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas plants and to coal.
In a few months, all of these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to ponder.
Champion of Europe of the wind, "which he gets 30 percent of its electricity, it is also one of the biggest users of coal and gas because of the intermittency of wind; under what, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill of more than 40 percent of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of the energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial tool on the national territory, French companies enjoy the cheapest electricity in Europe.
In fact, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would create a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory fine statements on the redevelopment of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially as they are not opposed in principle to this energy, polls show.
Remember that the energy policy of our country has helped build an industrial sector 125 000 direct jobs and 410 000 induced jobs.
Heavily export, it causes a galaxy of SMEs specializing on international markets and makes them very creative non-relocatable jobs.
If France were to decide to get out of nuclear power, this would sacrifice many of these SMEs in reducing alarmingly 6 billion annual French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician ordered an EPR designed to operate 60 years while the decline of its manufacturer would be scheduled?
To solve the energy equation, we must admit that there is no source of electricity production of miracle, as there is diabolical.
The development by Areva solutions CO2 emitting little, nuclear and renewable, shows the complementarity of sources of energy. "
For the nuclear, maintain the highest level of security is an absolute imperative.
We have a safety authority in France, which has control intransigent and transparent on existing plants as on the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited the same obsession with security.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has suffered three serious accidents.
A single, Three Mile Island, intervened in normal operating conditions; it remained without consequence human or environmental.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human error caused the tragedy.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn the lessons of this accident, as it did for the previous two.
The product of this approach and cooperation between security authorities, operators and the French and German manufacturers, the PRT presents a design making it able to resist such phenomena.
So it is considered by all the electricians eager to build a plant, the judgment of its construction at Flamanville would be a wonderful gift to competitors of Areva and EDF in their leaving the way free to grab the leadership in the development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to leave the "emotion, dogmas and partisan tactics dominate a debate as crucial to the economic, financial and social situation of our country.
The immigration is a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized in various ways - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status "human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students who made the news, the interior minister (read Liberation of 23 May) proclaiming that France "did not need foreign talent, builders and restaurant servers.".
But it is rarely analysed in economic terms.
It is there on this issue a fairly broad consensus between left and right.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who said in 1976 that "¥900 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers," and left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden for the economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that we are prepared to pay towards immigrants.
In its programme, Francois Hollande is restricted to platitudes, indicating that the co-development will solve our "migration problem.".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps going off; but it is economically very costly.
As the recall economists and Ian Goldin, Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book summarising the latest knowledge on immigration (: How Migration Shaped orphans of Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among the experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and employment.
The fears of the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may substitute for national workers, particularly the low-skilled, exerting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary that substitutes for national employees, for most of the jobs in sectors in shortage of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors in which the training is not following the offer of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have trouble working in a country that has a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants are that the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% rise of migratory flows increase between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages in the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and to economic growth (high proportion of immigrants naturalized among American Nobel; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
The migrants also are net contributors of social systems, an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organisation estimated that, in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 years will make a net contribution (revenue less expenses) of 150,000 euros public budgets on average over the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to, at the start of the mandate, go look for the missing growth "with teeth.".
The teeth, to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, remains to think European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity; it is also a very fragile.
The European continent should remember him for having invented in Athens over two thousand years ago, has known throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, colonels in Greece.
Some were able to believe that it would be enough for democracy triomphât definitively of its enemies, to exercise the vote, and the exercise in the most direct way.
We know, since Napoleon "Little," it was a facility of thought.
The universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and may even be "instrument of oppression" as once the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation of powers and control, education, enlightenment, solidarity, economic and social justice.
The crisis in Europe that we live in is an economic crisis, but it is equally and a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinodie faked the Greek referendum will have to double value: the need for a return of powerful political, but also the disquieting sense of his impossibility, its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be outdated.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle today are displaced, and that, for many of them, the soldiers Republicans do more in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain to demand a succession of national referendums, organised the needs and dispersed.
A white sheet - European absolute monarch or a leap to empty in the nationalist withdrawal: what choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cut-off but a common exercise of calm and continuous, the choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There was no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - cannot be more where stop the list - because there is a crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe, which bends to the dictates of the markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe who is humiliated on the international stage.
It is concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but the whole of Europe who slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The emergency is to restore the popular sovereignty flying of the European project.
Because it is whole, Europeans can reduce the weight of their debts, free markets and prepare for the future in investing.
The crisis exit will involve decisions at European level which can be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After long fought this proposal socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is asking for European economic government.
Either.
But think without a democratic political integration and stronger, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must assume a new stage of European integration.
To make the Republic in France, it took "do" of Republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not be sufficient.
That lesson remains valid.
We must build a more integrated Europe economically.
This can only be done by building a more democratic Europe politically, a genuine European popular sovereignty.
In Europe, are Europeans.
The smart cards "without contact" spreading
The trade show the chip card opens Tuesday at 100-point, near Paris, in a climate optimistic.
The year 2011 should be complete on an 11% increase global sales of microprocessor cards (bank card, phone with a SIM card...), more than 6 billion units, according Eurosmart.
The most promising technology is that without contact which helps pay the transport or settle its purchases in approaching the card from a reader.
This year, 460 million smart cards without contact should be sold around the world, against 320 million a year earlier.
Their share should still progress in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent nearly 10% of the global market of the smart card (6,925 million cards).
Long the laggard of the Asia-Pacific region, Europe is gaining ground for contactless payment.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality and 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa contactless cards have been deployed.
But the supermarkets.
Carrefour has issued this year and 2.5 million cards Pass MasterCard without contact.
To move up a gear, it must now that banks equip their customers.
"Two big French institutions are committed to broadcast to the future of their customers' bank cards equipped for without contact," said Gerard Nébouy, director general Visa Europe France.
The banks are testing the payment by mobile
But this is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Few aircraft are now equipped with NFC technology (Near Field Communication) necessary to conduct transactions.
"They have fallen behind.".
"But they should finally have a real growth next year.".
"We are counting on the sale of 80 to 120 million units in 2012 in the world," said Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But banks take the lead.
The Credit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test from December to June to Caen.
The iPhone of some 200 customers and staff will be equipped with a holster authorizing the payment without contact.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And Societe Generale, too, said yesterday prepare the marketing of an offer to allow its customers to pay without contact with their mobile.
From the Sahara in Nigeria, the terrorist front extends
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and Boko Haram sect.
The long-standing, the ties between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Foreign Affairs Minister, Abdelkader Messahel, has even said that Algiers has now "satisfied.".
"The way the two organisations operate and the intelligence reports show that there is cooperation," he said without elaborating.
Paris seems to do a similar analysis.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger in January would have uncovered.
Kidnappés in a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of AQIM, Antoine Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day at the same time that several of their abductors during an operation by French special forces.
In the rubble of the speech, the Nigerien and French investigators to trace several phone chip belonging to terrorists.
Axis terrorist
The analysis of past calls to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers are particularly interested investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who has travelled extensively in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram and the other to a man who is close to AQIM and the sect.
"This is a step forward, but it should probably expect more formal evidence before talk of operational cooperation between AQIM and Boko Haram.".
"But it is possible.".
"We know for years that the sect enjoys financial support and external intellectuals and that she is increasingly active," said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months these "support" had been increasingly evident in the development and speeches of Boko Haram or operating methods, which involve the use of suicide bombers or explosives increasingly complex and even invoice as those used by AQIM.
The international community, to begin by Washington, has therefore put pressure on Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long viewed the group as a community of visionaries little worthy of interest.
A rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and fundamentalist iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram haoussa - which means "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in Muslim northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association has a rapid success.
It is politicizing and requires a strict observance of Sharia law while its militants committed the fight against the central government impious.
They aim of all churches, bars, authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants are particularly active, multiplying attacks against police stations.
The reaction of Abuja is, as usual, without nuance.
The military invests the city, there are 800 people.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
Therefore the sect will radicalise and leave his northern strongholds.
At last Christmas, she claims an attack that left 80 people dead in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it is still in Abuja that Boko Haram has secured police headquarters in a suicide attack, his first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be his first target.
The creation of a terrorist axis operating in Africa Mauritania to Somalia from Nigeria now anxious all security specialists.
So that AQIM has invested Mali and Niger, that Somalis of al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat to the heart of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppe warned against Boko Haram and is ready "to share all information.".
The world according to the Republican candidates for the presidency
On China, Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry vying to oversimplification and ignorance.
A America weakened by the crisis can manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
To listen to the Republican presidential candidates, voters may believe.
For a few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other multiplying thundering declarations and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican strong point.
On China, Iran, on aid to Israel, the slogans - often not supported - mounts.
Mitt Romney, best placed in the race for the nomination of the "Grand Old Party", has threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and the challenge "for manipulation of their currency," a theme porter in an America exasperated by the migration of swathes of its industry to Asia.
Too bad if it must involve the outbreak of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, former Obama in China and only candidate to have a vision of sophisticated foreign policy, has failed to strangle face an attitude that "gloat" emotions.
He called for a tough but constructive dialogue with Beijing (the current position of Obama).
But Huntsman, which is in the depths of the polls, is inaudible.
In the image of Reagan
Romney also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to halt its nuclear program.
"If I am elected, I will stop Iran, he fanfaronné."
"If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb."
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing in its obligations to the partner.
The entrepreneur Herman Cain, second candidate, it was an embarrassing lack of records.
Recently, he called to counter the military threat China because Beijing "is trying to develop a nuclear capability" - apparently ignoring the fact that China holds the military atom since 1964.
The Texas governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants to strikes against Iran, is ready to commit to the U.S. military in Mexico against the drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and Michele Bachmann.
It is far from the 2008 Republican presidential nominee, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president counter that Reagan also had simple ideas and he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and he had to put water in his wine in counterterrorism.
They insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the departure too rushed "boys" in Iraq, his dithering in Libya, sticky label him as weak.
But the attack is not so easy.
The population judge rather positive assessment of national security to Obama, who has eliminated Bin Laden.
Since Iraq, it is wary of military interventions that lead to deadlock.
And, arguing that it must rebuild economically America to resurrect his leadership, Obama hits.
The North Stream, new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia from the bottom of the Baltic Sea, came into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a bang.
More than 500 guests including four Heads of State and Government participated last Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and smorgasbord end, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new pipeline that connects directly under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, the German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, the French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the wheel of the valve together commander the entry of Russian gas in the western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1 224 km from the area of St. Petersburg in the Land of Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed by the end of 2012, the total to 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to the entire French consumption.
And we already mentioned the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time for this huge project has the air of victory.
The project had been strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will enable us to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding land crossing by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh in on Russia by threatening to shut down access to European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new Molotov-Ribbentrop pact," in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for Poland in 1939.
That is to say if the issue is politically sensitive.
The Western Europe, supporting the Russian proposal, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is the price of a weakening of Europe of energy, since the project has created a rift between Europeans, East and West.
Russia has known, in five years ago, to his vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, strongly consumers of gas, and whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," Fillon said in opening this pipeline, showing how the major gas contracts are also political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles posted by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number to Lubmin, to the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine is in gainé steel tube of concrete to protect against the anchors of ships.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, 200 metres on average.
For the build, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the North Stream.
He also took measures to protect the flora and fauna.
The tube is a long snake of heavy metal, as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing stops on its entire length: or valve, or maintenance station.
A platform of control was planned off Sweden, but officials have abandoned the project while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state company moving permanently off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas content in the pipeline escapes in the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have planned the welds to know a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is provided by a robot under - sailor, dragged by a ship for external monitoring, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is brought inside the tube, wide a metre in diameter, and it is driven by the gas.
In the end, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 feet a second, precise information on the possible distortions of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate 50 years without any compensation.
The movement of the gas is simply provided by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 to the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains a 51% stake.
If there are joined the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie's and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, named Nord Stream, build and operate the pipeline.
She has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company for 20 years, the entire gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually taken," said Jens Müller.
The funding of the construction of the pipeline has been assured to 30% by shareholders and 70 percent by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are safe to return to their expenses, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline pine planted.
Some 4.5 metres tall, valves, form the exit door of gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and characteristics of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas each hour.
At full capacity, this will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine notebook, a mark.
Established about 15 years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine to restore the taste of writing.
It smacks of adventure, hours to write to light a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable with his black rectangular coverage, his elastic, leaves a white colour, as outdated by the time.
Still, the Moleskine notebook as we know today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decides to launch a notebook design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, the launch of the new product.
The book is based on an ancient technique of production, the mole skin (skin of mole) which means a cotton veneer used to cover benches by example.
This type of notebook was very popular writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has returned to the fore a subject old and forgotten, that was an icon of the avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," said Maria Sebregondi, since the head of the mark in Modo Modo.
The success is.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales rose 26 percent to 12.7 million pieces.
It is far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3 000 books were designed.
Moleskine transcends borders Italian and exported in 70 countries, France until the United States.
It is difficult to establish a sketch of the buyer, because the notebook seduced both the businessman that the student and professionals.
In the image of Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its infancy, has almost 100 today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its books in the bookshops, the Internet to small shops in downtown and was able to impose its identity.
"We have followed the air time and this new writing, despite the rise of e-mail," said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signing with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects and artists put their own book.
In August, it has also launched a leopard, coverage at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this will be cultural, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, covers of computer... The brand is on a whole range of mediums.
A success that was envied: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why the unemployment rate for disabled workers remains so high?
About 19 percent of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled opens today.
Despite a proactive policy implementation in 2005, the unemployment rate of disabled people is still more than twice the average: 19% versus 9% for the whole population.
Décourageant?
"No, said Eric Blanchet, director general of the Adapt, the association which organises the week for the employment of disabled."
"The progress made since 15 years are considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"It is still a great deal to do."
It must be said that for the unemployed disabled, the many obstacles remain before access to employment.
They are aged: 37 percent have more than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 percent do not have the box and on the 2.3 million students in higher education, 10 000 only are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, against 38% on average.
In short, all of which criteria hampering the return to employment, and which "are the crux of the problem," said Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That is for the brakes objectives.
The unspoken, attitudes are changing, but too slowly.
A study in April by the association IMS - Entreprendre for the City indicated that managers surveyed "a low level of knowledge of disability," with a "over-representation of people in wheelchairs, intellectual or psychological functioning.".
As a result, private companies of more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the goal of employment 6% of disabled workers, set in a law... 1987.
The latest figures available, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3 percent," said Pierre Blanc, director general of the Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with the law.
The evidence: the number of institutions "taxed", as the amounts paid, declined between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 46 000 structures (and 606 to 480 million euros).
"The law of 2005, which increased contributions, has created a pressure on companies," said Pierre White.
"But this improvement also reflected a real awareness, especially in the big groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 percent of the establishments of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, against 82 percent of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
